/* PasstheEPPP — Expanded Question Bank Batch 2 */
(function(){
    if (typeof EPPPData === 'undefined') return;

    const batch2 = [
        // ===== Domain 1: Biological Bases of Behavior =====
        {domainId:1, q:"A patient with damage to the amygdala would most likely exhibit which of the following?", options:["Difficulty forming new explicit memories","Impaired fear conditioning","Loss of motor coordination","Inability to produce speech"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"The amygdala is critical for emotional processing, particularly fear conditioning. Bilateral amygdala damage (as in Klüver-Bucy syndrome) results in reduced fear responses, emotional blunting, and impaired recognition of fearful expressions. Memory consolidation involves the hippocampus, motor coordination the cerebellum, and speech production Broca's area."},
        {domainId:1, q:"Which neurotransmitter system is primarily targeted by selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs)?", options:["Dopaminergic system","Serotonergic system","Noradrenergic system","GABAergic system"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"SSRIs selectively block the reuptake of serotonin (5-HT) at the presynaptic terminal, increasing serotonin availability in the synaptic cleft. This mechanism underlies their use in treating depression, anxiety disorders, and OCD. They have minimal direct effects on dopamine, norepinephrine, or GABA systems."},
        {domainId:1, q:"A clinical vignette: A 45-year-old man presents with progressive muscle weakness, fasciculations, and difficulty swallowing. Cognitive function is preserved. Which neural structure is primarily affected?", options:["Upper motor neurons only","Lower motor neurons only","Both upper and lower motor neurons","Cerebellar Purkinje cells"], answer:2, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"The presentation describes amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS), which involves degeneration of both upper and lower motor neurons. This produces a combination of upper motor neuron signs (spasticity, hyperreflexia) and lower motor neuron signs (weakness, fasciculations, atrophy). Cognitive function is typically preserved in classic ALS."},
        {domainId:1, q:"The blood-brain barrier is primarily formed by which type of cells?", options:["Astrocytes and endothelial cells","Schwann cells","Oligodendrocytes","Microglia"], answer:0, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"The blood-brain barrier (BBB) is formed by tight junctions between capillary endothelial cells, supported by astrocyte foot processes (end-feet) that wrap around blood vessels. This barrier selectively restricts the passage of substances from the bloodstream to the brain, protecting the CNS from toxins while allowing essential nutrients through."},
        {domainId:1, q:"Wernicke's encephalopathy is caused by a deficiency in which vitamin?", options:["Vitamin B12","Vitamin B1 (thiamine)","Vitamin D","Vitamin C"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Wernicke's encephalopathy results from thiamine (vitamin B1) deficiency, commonly seen in chronic alcoholism. The classic triad includes confusion, ataxia, and ophthalmoplegia. If untreated, it can progress to Korsakoff's syndrome, characterized by severe anterograde amnesia and confabulation."},
        {domainId:1, q:"Which brain structure plays a critical role in the regulation of circadian rhythms?", options:["Pineal gland","Suprachiasmatic nucleus","Reticular activating system","Locus coeruleus"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"The suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN) of the hypothalamus is the master circadian clock. It receives direct input from the retina via the retinohypothalamic tract and coordinates circadian rhythms throughout the body. The pineal gland produces melatonin under SCN control but is not the primary pacemaker."},
        {domainId:1, q:"Broca's aphasia is characterized by:", options:["Fluent but incomprehensible speech","Non-fluent, effortful speech with preserved comprehension","Inability to repeat spoken language","Complete loss of all language functions"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Broca's aphasia (expressive/non-fluent aphasia) results from damage to Broca's area in the left frontal lobe. Patients produce effortful, telegraphic speech with poor grammar but relatively preserved comprehension. This contrasts with Wernicke's aphasia, which features fluent but semantically empty speech with impaired comprehension."},
        {domainId:1, q:"A patient taking a typical antipsychotic develops involuntary repetitive movements of the tongue and lips after months of treatment. This condition is best described as:", options:["Acute dystonia","Akathisia","Tardive dyskinesia","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Tardive dyskinesia (TD) develops after prolonged use of dopamine receptor antagonists (typical antipsychotics). It presents with involuntary, repetitive movements primarily affecting orofacial muscles (tongue, lips, jaw). Unlike acute dystonia (rapid onset) or akathisia (inner restlessness), TD is a late-onset condition that can be irreversible."},
        {domainId:1, q:"Which lobe of the brain is most associated with executive functioning, planning, and decision-making?", options:["Temporal lobe","Parietal lobe","Occipital lobe","Frontal lobe"], answer:3, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"The frontal lobe, particularly the prefrontal cortex, is the primary seat of executive functions including planning, decision-making, impulse control, working memory, and cognitive flexibility. Damage to this area can result in personality changes, poor judgment, and difficulty with complex tasks (as famously observed in the case of Phineas Gage)."},
        {domainId:1, q:"The fight-or-flight response is primarily mediated by the:", options:["Parasympathetic nervous system","Somatic nervous system","Sympathetic nervous system","Enteric nervous system"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"The sympathetic nervous system (SNS) mediates the fight-or-flight response, preparing the body for emergency action by increasing heart rate, dilating pupils, redirecting blood flow to muscles, and releasing epinephrine and norepinephrine. The parasympathetic system ('rest and digest') generally opposes these effects."},

        // ===== Domain 2: Cognitive-Affective Bases of Behavior =====
        {domainId:2, q:"According to dual-process theory, System 1 thinking is characterized by:", options:["Slow, deliberate, and analytical processing","Fast, automatic, and intuitive processing","Exclusive use of working memory","Conscious, effortful reasoning"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Dual-process theory (Kahneman, 2011) distinguishes between System 1 (fast, automatic, intuitive, effortless) and System 2 (slow, deliberate, analytical, effortful) thinking. System 1 operates largely unconsciously and handles routine decisions, while System 2 is engaged for complex problem-solving and novel situations."},
        {domainId:2, q:"A clinical vignette: A patient can recall detailed events from their childhood but cannot remember what they had for breakfast. This pattern most likely reflects impairment in:", options:["Procedural memory","Semantic memory","Anterograde memory","Retrograde memory"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Anterograde amnesia is the inability to form new memories after the onset of the condition, while retrograde amnesia involves loss of memories formed before the onset. This patient retains old memories but cannot form new ones, consistent with anterograde amnesia, commonly seen in hippocampal damage."},
        {domainId:2, q:"The phenomenon where people are more likely to recall the first and last items in a list is known as:", options:["The recency effect","The primacy effect","The serial position effect","The spacing effect"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"The serial position effect encompasses both the primacy effect (better recall of early items due to elaborative rehearsal and long-term memory storage) and the recency effect (better recall of recent items still in short-term memory). The U-shaped recall curve was first demonstrated by Murdock (1962)."},
        {domainId:2, q:"According to Lazarus's cognitive appraisal theory, the experience of stress depends primarily on:", options:["The objective severity of the stressor","An individual's appraisal of the situation and their coping resources","The frequency of stressful events","Neurochemical responses to threat"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Lazarus and Folkman (1984) proposed that stress results from a two-stage appraisal process: primary appraisal (evaluating whether a situation is threatening) and secondary appraisal (evaluating one's resources to cope). The same event can be experienced differently depending on these cognitive evaluations."},
        {domainId:2, q:"The 'cocktail party effect' is an example of:", options:["Divided attention","Selective attention","Sustained attention","Inattentional blindness"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"The cocktail party effect (Cherry, 1953) demonstrates selective attention — the ability to focus on one particular stimulus while filtering out competing stimuli. At a noisy party, you can attend to one conversation while ignoring others, but your name mentioned elsewhere can still capture your attention."},
        {domainId:2, q:"What is the typical capacity of short-term memory according to Miller's (1956) research?", options:["3 ± 1 items","5 ± 2 items","7 ± 2 items","12 ± 3 items"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"George Miller's (1956) classic paper 'The Magical Number Seven, Plus or Minus Two' established that short-term memory has a capacity of approximately 7 ± 2 items (chunks). This capacity can be expanded through chunking — grouping individual items into meaningful units."},
        {domainId:2, q:"The misinformation effect, as studied by Elizabeth Loftus, demonstrates that:", options:["Eyewitness testimony is always reliable","Post-event information can alter memory for an original event","Memories cannot be influenced after encoding","False memories only occur in children"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Loftus's research demonstrated that post-event misinformation (e.g., leading questions) can alter or create memories for events that didn't occur. Her car accident studies showed that changing a single word in a question (e.g., 'smashed' vs. 'hit') significantly influenced speed estimates and false memory for broken glass."},
        {domainId:2, q:"According to the Yerkes-Dodson law, performance on complex tasks is optimal at:", options:["High arousal levels","Low to moderate arousal levels","Very low arousal levels","Arousal level is irrelevant"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"The Yerkes-Dodson law (1908) proposes an inverted-U relationship between arousal and performance. For complex tasks, performance peaks at low to moderate arousal; excessive arousal impairs performance. For simple tasks, higher arousal levels are optimal. This has implications for test anxiety and performance under pressure."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Learned helplessness, as originally described by Seligman, occurs when:", options:["Organisms learn that their responses have no effect on outcomes","Positive reinforcement is inconsistently applied","Classical conditioning leads to aversion","Operant conditioning produces superstitious behavior"], answer:0, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Seligman and Maier (1967) demonstrated learned helplessness when dogs exposed to inescapable shocks later failed to escape avoidable shocks. The organisms learned that their behavior had no effect on outcomes, leading to passivity and depression-like symptoms. This model has been influential in understanding depression."},
        {domainId:2, q:"The just-world hypothesis refers to:", options:["The belief that people get what they deserve","The theory that the world is objectively fair","A cognitive bias toward optimism","The tendency to blame external factors for failures"], answer:0, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"The just-world hypothesis (Lerner, 1980) is the cognitive bias that the world is fundamentally fair — good things happen to good people and bad things happen to bad people. This belief can lead to victim blaming and serves a psychological function of maintaining a sense of control and predictability."},

        // ===== Domain 3: Social & Cultural Bases of Behavior =====
        {domainId:3, q:"The concept of 'intersectionality' was introduced by:", options:["Derald Wing Sue","Kimberlé Crenshaw","Patricia Arredondo","Janet Helms"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Kimberlé Crenshaw coined the term 'intersectionality' in 1989 to describe how overlapping social identities (race, gender, class, sexuality) create unique experiences of discrimination and privilege. This framework is critical in multicultural psychology for understanding that identity categories interact rather than exist independently."},
        {domainId:3, q:"According to Berry's acculturation model, which strategy involves maintaining one's heritage culture while also adopting the dominant culture?", options:["Assimilation","Separation","Integration","Marginalization"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Berry's (1997) acculturation model identifies four strategies based on two dimensions: maintaining heritage culture and adopting dominant culture. Integration (high on both) is generally associated with the best psychological outcomes. Assimilation favors the dominant culture, separation maintains only heritage culture, and marginalization rejects both."},
        {domainId:3, q:"The 'social identity threat' model explains:", options:["Why people conform to group norms","How negative stereotypes can impair performance","Why groups develop hierarchies","How cultural values are transmitted"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Social identity threat (related to stereotype threat) occurs when individuals are aware of negative stereotypes about their group and fear confirming them. This psychological burden can impair cognitive performance, reduce working memory capacity, and create anxiety. Steele and Aronson (1995) demonstrated this effect with standardized test performance."},
        {domainId:3, q:"In multicultural counseling, the term 'cultural encapsulation' refers to:", options:["A counselor's deep understanding of another culture","A counselor's tendency to operate from their own cultural assumptions","The process of acculturation","A client's resistance to therapy"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Cultural encapsulation (Wrenn, 1962) describes counselors who substitute their own cultural assumptions for reality, ignore cultural differences, and apply techniques universally without cultural sensitivity. This represents a major barrier to effective cross-cultural counseling and highlights the need for multicultural competence."},
        {domainId:3, q:"The bystander effect, as demonstrated by Darley and Latané, refers to:", options:["Increased helping behavior in groups","Decreased helping behavior as the number of bystanders increases","Group polarization in emergency situations","Social facilitation during crises"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"The bystander effect (Darley & Latané, 1968), inspired by the Kitty Genovese case, found that people are less likely to help when others are present. Key mechanisms include diffusion of responsibility, pluralistic ignorance (looking to others for cues), and evaluation apprehension. The more bystanders, the less likely any individual will intervene."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Social comparison theory (Festinger, 1954) proposes that people:", options:["Evaluate their abilities and opinions by comparing themselves to others","Always compare themselves to those who are superior","Avoid social comparison when self-esteem is low","Only engage in comparison within their in-group"], answer:0, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Festinger's social comparison theory posits that people have a fundamental drive to evaluate their abilities and opinions, and when objective standards are unavailable, they compare themselves to similar others. Upward comparisons (with superior others) can motivate improvement, while downward comparisons (with inferior others) can boost self-esteem."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Individualistic cultures, compared to collectivistic cultures, tend to:", options:["Emphasize group harmony and social obligations","Value personal achievement and autonomy","Prioritize extended family connections","Use high-context communication styles"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Individualistic cultures (e.g., U.S., Western Europe) emphasize personal goals, autonomy, self-expression, and individual rights. Collectivistic cultures (e.g., East Asian, Latin American) prioritize group harmony, interdependence, social obligations, and family connections. This dimension (Hofstede, 1980) is fundamental to cross-cultural psychology."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Which model describes therapist multicultural competence as including awareness, knowledge, and skills?", options:["Berry's acculturation model","Sue's tripartite model","Helms' racial identity model","Bronfenbrenner's ecological model"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Sue, Arredondo, and McDavis (1992) proposed the tripartite model of multicultural competence consisting of: (1) awareness of one's own cultural values and biases, (2) knowledge of clients' worldviews and cultural backgrounds, and (3) skills to implement culturally appropriate interventions. This framework is foundational in multicultural counseling education."},

        // ===== Domain 4: Growth & Lifespan Development =====
        {domainId:4, q:"According to Bowlby's attachment theory, which type of attachment is characterized by a child's distress upon separation and difficulty being soothed upon reunion?", options:["Secure attachment","Avoidant attachment","Anxious-resistant (ambivalent) attachment","Disorganized attachment"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Anxious-resistant (ambivalent) attachment involves intense distress during separation with ambivalent behavior at reunion — the child may cling to the caregiver but also resist comfort. This pattern develops with inconsistent caregiving. Secure children are distressed but easily comforted, avoidant children show minimal distress, and disorganized children show contradictory behaviors."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Erikson's stage of 'generativity vs. stagnation' typically occurs during:", options:["Adolescence (12-18 years)","Early adulthood (18-40 years)","Middle adulthood (40-65 years)","Late adulthood (65+ years)"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Generativity vs. stagnation is the seventh of Erikson's eight psychosocial stages, occurring in middle adulthood. Generativity involves contributing to society and nurturing the next generation through parenting, mentoring, or creative work. Failure to achieve generativity leads to stagnation, self-absorption, and feelings of unproductiveness."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Vygotsky's concept of the 'zone of proximal development' (ZPD) refers to:", options:["Tasks a child can complete independently","The gap between what a child can do alone and what they can do with guidance","The critical period for language acquisition","The stage of cognitive development preceding formal operations"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"The ZPD is the distance between a child's actual developmental level (independent problem-solving) and potential developmental level (problem-solving under adult guidance or with more capable peers). Scaffolding — providing temporary support that is gradually withdrawn — is the key instructional strategy based on this concept."},
        {domainId:4, q:"A child who understands that changing the shape of a ball of clay doesn't change its amount demonstrates:", options:["Object permanence","Centration","Conservation","Reversibility"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Conservation is the understanding that certain properties of objects (quantity, volume, number) remain unchanged despite changes in their appearance. This ability develops during Piaget's concrete operational stage (ages 7-11). Children in the preoperational stage fail conservation tasks because they focus on one perceptual dimension (centration)."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Kohlberg's postconventional level of moral reasoning is characterized by:", options:["Obedience to authority to avoid punishment","Conformity to social norms and laws","Principled reasoning based on universal ethical principles","Self-interest and instrumental exchange"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Postconventional moral reasoning (Stages 5-6) involves principled reasoning about universal ethical principles that may transcend specific laws. Stage 5 emphasizes the social contract and individual rights, while Stage 6 involves abstract justice and conscience-based decisions. Research suggests few adults consistently operate at this level."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Ainsworth's Strange Situation procedure was designed to assess:", options:["Cognitive development in infants","Temperament in toddlers","Attachment patterns in infants","Emotional regulation in preschoolers"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Mary Ainsworth's Strange Situation (1970) is a standardized laboratory procedure for assessing infant attachment quality in 12-18 month olds. It involves eight episodes of separations and reunions between infant and caregiver, with the infant's behavior coded to classify attachment as secure, avoidant, resistant/ambivalent, or disorganized."},
        {domainId:4, q:"The concept of 'theory of mind' typically develops around age:", options:["1-2 years","3-5 years","7-9 years","11-13 years"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Theory of mind (ToM) — the ability to understand that others have beliefs, desires, and intentions different from one's own — typically develops between ages 3-5. The classic false-belief task (Sally-Anne test) demonstrates this milestone. Children with autism spectrum disorder often show delays in ToM development."},
        {domainId:4, q:"According to Kübler-Ross, the five stages of grief are:", options:["Shock, anger, guilt, depression, recovery","Denial, anger, bargaining, depression, acceptance","Numbness, yearning, disorganization, reorganization, resolution","Alarm, resistance, exhaustion, adaptation, growth"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Elisabeth Kübler-Ross (1969) proposed five stages of grief: denial, anger, bargaining, depression, and acceptance. While widely influential, this model has been criticized for suggesting a linear progression. Current grief research recognizes that grief is highly individual, stages may overlap or recur, and not everyone experiences all stages."},

        // ===== Domain 5: Assessment & Diagnosis =====
        {domainId:5, q:"A test with high internal consistency but low test-retest reliability most likely:", options:["Measures a stable trait accurately","Contains items that measure the same construct but the construct fluctuates over time","Has high criterion validity","Is poorly standardized"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"High internal consistency (Cronbach's alpha) indicates items within the test measure the same construct cohesively. Low test-retest reliability suggests scores change across time. This pattern suggests the test reliably measures a construct that itself fluctuates (e.g., mood states rather than personality traits)."},
        {domainId:5, q:"In the MMPI-2, the F scale is primarily used to assess:", options:["Faking good (social desirability)","Infrequent or deviant responses","Defensiveness","Random responding"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"The F (Infrequency) scale on the MMPI-2 contains items endorsed by less than 10% of the normative sample. Elevated F scores may indicate genuine psychopathology, exaggeration of symptoms (faking bad/malingering), random responding, or reading difficulties. It serves as a validity indicator to assess the quality of the test-taking approach."},
        {domainId:5, q:"Which of the following is NOT a characteristic of a projective test?", options:["Ambiguous stimuli","Standardized scoring systems","Open-ended responses","Assessment of unconscious processes"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Projective tests (Rorschach, TAT) use ambiguous stimuli and open-ended responses to assess unconscious processes. While the Exner Comprehensive System has improved Rorschach scoring, projective tests traditionally lack the highly standardized scoring systems characteristic of objective tests. This has been a major criticism regarding their psychometric properties."},
        {domainId:5, q:"The standard error of measurement (SEM) is used to:", options:["Determine test validity","Calculate the confidence interval around an individual's true score","Establish test-retest reliability","Assess cultural bias in test items"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"The SEM estimates the range within which an individual's true score likely falls. It is calculated from the test's reliability coefficient and standard deviation: SEM = SD × √(1 - reliability). Higher reliability results in smaller SEM, indicating more precise measurement. The 95% confidence interval is approximately ±2 SEMs around the observed score."},
        {domainId:5, q:"A T-score of 70 on a standardized personality measure corresponds to:", options:["1 standard deviation above the mean","2 standard deviations above the mean","3 standard deviations above the mean","The 50th percentile"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"T-scores have a mean of 50 and a standard deviation of 10. A T-score of 70 is 2 SDs above the mean, corresponding approximately to the 98th percentile. On clinical instruments like the MMPI-2, a T-score ≥ 65 is often used as the clinical cutoff, indicating significant elevation compared to the normative sample."},
        {domainId:5, q:"Criterion-referenced tests differ from norm-referenced tests in that they:", options:["Compare performance to a fixed standard rather than other examinees","Always use standardized scoring","Have higher reliability coefficients","Are used exclusively in educational settings"], answer:0, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Criterion-referenced tests evaluate performance against a predetermined standard or criterion (e.g., minimum competency for licensure), while norm-referenced tests compare individuals to a normative group. The EPPP itself is a criterion-referenced exam — candidates must achieve a minimum scaled score (typically 500) regardless of others' performance."},
        {domainId:5, q:"Convergent validity is demonstrated when a test:", options:["Predicts future behavior accurately","Correlates highly with other measures of the same construct","Shows low correlation with measures of different constructs","Has consistent results across different raters"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Convergent validity, a component of construct validity, is established when a test correlates highly with other measures of the same or similar constructs. For example, a new anxiety measure should correlate highly with established anxiety scales (convergent validity) but show lower correlations with measures of unrelated constructs like extraversion (discriminant validity)."},
        {domainId:5, q:"Which Wechsler subtest is most sensitive to intellectual decline in older adults?", options:["Vocabulary","Information","Digit Symbol-Coding","Comprehension"], answer:2, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Digit Symbol-Coding (now Coding) is a performance-based subtest measuring processing speed, attention, and psychomotor skills — abilities that naturally decline with aging (fluid intelligence). In contrast, Vocabulary and Information tap crystallized intelligence, which tends to remain stable or even improve with age. This differential pattern is useful in neuropsychological assessment of cognitive decline."},

        // ===== Domain 6: Treatment/Intervention =====
        {domainId:6, q:"In motivational interviewing, 'rolling with resistance' refers to:", options:["Directly confronting client denial","Avoiding the topic of change entirely","Acknowledging the client's perspective without arguing","Using paradoxical interventions to create resistance"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Rolling with resistance is a core principle of motivational interviewing (Miller & Rollnick, 2002). Rather than confronting or arguing with ambivalent clients, the therapist acknowledges their perspective, reframes statements, and avoids power struggles. This approach reduces defensiveness and allows the client to explore their own motivations for change."},
        {domainId:6, q:"The therapeutic technique of 'empty chair' is most associated with which approach?", options:["Psychoanalytic therapy","Cognitive-behavioral therapy","Gestalt therapy","Solution-focused brief therapy"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"The empty chair technique is a hallmark of Gestalt therapy (Fritz Perls). The client engages in dialogue with an imagined person, aspect of self, or emotion seated in an empty chair. This experiential technique promotes awareness, emotional expression, and integration of polarities. It has been adapted and used in emotion-focused therapy (EFT) as well."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Dialectical Behavior Therapy (DBT) was originally developed to treat:", options:["Generalized anxiety disorder","Borderline personality disorder","Major depressive disorder","Obsessive-compulsive disorder"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Marsha Linehan developed DBT specifically for chronically suicidal individuals with borderline personality disorder (BPD). DBT integrates CBT skills training with mindfulness practices and dialectical philosophy (accepting and changing simultaneously). The four skill modules are mindfulness, distress tolerance, emotion regulation, and interpersonal effectiveness."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Which of the following is a key concept in Acceptance and Commitment Therapy (ACT)?", options:["Cognitive restructuring","Psychological flexibility","Systematic desensitization","Free association"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Psychological flexibility — the ability to contact the present moment fully and change or persist in behavior in service of chosen values — is the central concept of ACT (Hayes et al., 2006). ACT uses six core processes: cognitive defusion, acceptance, present moment awareness, self-as-context, values, and committed action. Unlike CBT, ACT doesn't aim to change thoughts but to change one's relationship with them."},
        {domainId:6, q:"The 'Dodo bird verdict' in psychotherapy research suggests that:", options:["CBT is clearly superior to all other therapies","Psychodynamic therapy is the most effective approach","Different therapeutic approaches tend to produce equivalent outcomes","Medication is always more effective than psychotherapy"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"The Dodo bird verdict (Rosenzweig, 1936; Luborsky et al., 1975) holds that when common factors are controlled for, different psychotherapy modalities produce roughly equivalent outcomes. This suggests that common therapeutic factors (alliance, empathy, positive expectation) may be more important than specific techniques. This remains one of the most debated findings in psychotherapy research."},
        {domainId:6, q:"In exposure therapy for phobias, 'flooding' involves:", options:["Gradual exposure starting with least anxiety-provoking stimuli","Immediate and prolonged exposure to the most feared stimulus","Cognitive restructuring before any exposure","Imaginal exposure only"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Flooding (implosive therapy) involves immediate, prolonged exposure to the highest-intensity feared stimulus until anxiety naturally diminishes through habituation. Unlike systematic desensitization (which uses gradual hierarchy), flooding does not build up gradually. While effective, it can be distressing, and clients may drop out if the anxiety becomes overwhelming."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Evidence-based practice (EBP) in psychology integrates:", options:["Only randomized controlled trial results","Best research evidence, clinical expertise, and patient characteristics","Clinician preference and insurance requirements","Theoretical orientation and supervisor guidance"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"The APA Presidential Task Force (2006) defined EBP as 'the integration of the best available research with clinical expertise in the context of patient characteristics, culture, and preferences.' This three-legged stool approach recognizes that effective practice requires more than research alone — clinical judgment and patient factors are equally essential."},
        {domainId:6, q:"The concept of 'therapeutic alliance' correlates most strongly with:", options:["Treatment length","Therapist's theoretical orientation","Psychotherapy outcomes","Type of presenting problem"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Research consistently shows that therapeutic alliance (Bordin, 1979) — the collaborative relationship between therapist and client encompassing agreement on goals, agreement on tasks, and the bond — is one of the strongest predictors of psychotherapy outcomes across modalities. The alliance accounts for approximately 5-8% of outcome variance, which is substantial in psychotherapy research."},

        // ===== Domain 7: Research Methods =====
        {domainId:7, q:"In a randomized controlled trial, the purpose of random assignment is to:", options:["Ensure equal sample sizes in each group","Maximize external validity","Control for confounding variables by distributing them equally","Increase statistical power"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Random assignment distributes both known and unknown confounding variables approximately equally across experimental and control groups, establishing internal validity. This is the key advantage of true experiments over quasi-experiments. Without random assignment, pre-existing group differences could explain outcome differences, making causal inferences impossible."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Cohen's d of 0.8 represents:", options:["A small effect size","A medium effect size","A large effect size","A very large effect size"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Cohen (1988) proposed conventional benchmarks for effect sizes: d = 0.2 (small), d = 0.5 (medium), d = 0.8 (large). Cohen's d represents the standardized mean difference between two groups in terms of standard deviation units. A d of 0.8 means the means differ by 0.8 standard deviations, which represents a clearly visible difference."},
        {domainId:7, q:"A Type I error in hypothesis testing is:", options:["Failing to reject a false null hypothesis","Rejecting a true null hypothesis","A measurement error in data collection","Using the wrong statistical test"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"A Type I error (false positive/alpha error) occurs when the null hypothesis is true but is incorrectly rejected. The probability of a Type I error is set by alpha (typically .05). A Type II error (false negative/beta error) is the failure to reject a false null hypothesis. Statistical power (1 - beta) is the probability of correctly rejecting a false null hypothesis."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Which research design is most appropriate for studying rare conditions or unique clinical presentations?", options:["Randomized controlled trial","Cross-sectional survey","Single-case experimental design","Meta-analysis"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Single-case (N=1) experimental designs are ideal for studying rare conditions, unique presentations, or situations where large samples are impractical. They involve repeated measurement of one or few participants with manipulation of independent variables (e.g., ABAB reversal, multiple baseline). While limited in generalizability, they allow causal inferences and are valuable in clinical practice."},
        {domainId:7, q:"The correlation between therapist empathy and client outcomes would best be described as:", options:["A causal relationship","An associative relationship","An inverse correlation","A spurious correlation"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correlational research reveals associations between variables but cannot establish causation. Even when empathy consistently correlates with better outcomes, the relationship is associative — we cannot conclude empathy causes improvement because unmeasured variables (e.g., client motivation, problem type) might explain both. Experimental manipulation would be needed for causal claims."},

        // ===== Domain 8: Professional Ethics =====
        {domainId:8, q:"Under the APA Ethics Code, psychologists may terminate therapy when:", options:["The client cannot pay for services","The psychologist believes therapy is no longer needed and termination would not harm the client","The client disagrees with the treatment approach","Any of the above, without conditions"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"APA Standard 10.10 states that psychologists terminate therapy when it becomes reasonably clear that therapy is no longer needed, is not benefiting the client, or the client is at risk of harm from continued treatment. Inability to pay alone is not sufficient grounds; the psychologist must make reasonable efforts to provide alternative resources (Standard 10.10c)."},
        {domainId:8, q:"Tarasoff v. Regents of the University of California established:", options:["The right to refuse treatment","A duty to protect identifiable third parties from serious harm","The confidentiality of therapy records","The standard for informed consent"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Tarasoff v. Regents (1976) established that mental health professionals have a duty to protect identifiable potential victims when a client makes a serious threat. The original 1974 ruling emphasized 'duty to warn,' while the 1976 ruling broadened this to 'duty to protect,' which can include warning, hospitalizing the client, or informing police."},
        {domainId:8, q:"The principle of 'beneficence and nonmaleficence' in psychology ethics means:", options:["Psychologists should always maximize client benefit regardless of risks","Psychologists must do no harm and strive to benefit those with whom they work","Psychologists should prioritize research over clinical care","Clients always have the right to choose their treatment"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Principle A (Beneficence and Nonmaleficence) of the APA Ethics Code requires psychologists to strive to benefit those with whom they work and take care to do no harm. When conflicts arise, psychologists must balance potential benefits against possible risks. This principle underpins informed consent, risk-benefit analysis, and the obligation to maintain competence."},
        {domainId:8, q:"A psychologist discovers that a supervisee has been engaging in a dual relationship with a client. The psychologist's ethical obligation is to:", options:["Ignore it if the client hasn't complained","Address the issue with the supervisee and take appropriate corrective action","Immediately report the supervisee to the licensing board","Terminate supervision immediately"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"APA Standard 7.06 requires supervisors to take reasonable steps to ensure that supervisees comply with ethics codes. The supervisor should first address the concern directly with the supervisee, provide education about dual relationships, and take corrective action. Immediate reporting to the board without first addressing the issue would not be the appropriate first step unless the situation involves imminent harm."},
        {domainId:8, q:"According to APA ethics, competence to practice requires:", options:["A doctoral degree only","Education, training, supervised experience, and ongoing professional development","At least 10 years of clinical experience","Board certification in a specialty area"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"APA Standard 2.01 requires that psychologists practice only within the boundaries of their competence, based on education, training, supervised experience, consultation, study, or professional experience. Maintaining competence requires ongoing professional development, staying current with research, and seeking consultation or additional training when working in new areas."}
    ];

    // Add to domains
    batch2.forEach(q => {
        const domain = EPPPData.domains.find(d => d.id === q.domainId);
        if (domain) {
            domain.questions.push({
                q: q.q,
                options: q.options,
                answer: q.answer,
                difficulty: q.difficulty,
                rationale: q.rationale,
                domainId: q.domainId,
                domainName: domain.name
            });
        }
    });

    console.log(`PasstheEPPP: Loaded ${batch2.length} additional questions (batch 2).`);
})();


// --- Source: data_expanded3.js ---
/* PasstheEPPP — Expanded Question Bank Batch 3 */
(function(){
    if (typeof EPPPData === 'undefined') return;

    const batch3 = [
        // ===== Domain 1: Biological Bases of Behavior =====
        {domainId:1, q:"Chronic stress is most associated with dysfunction in which hormonal axis?", options:["Hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal (HPG) axis","Hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis","Hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid (HPT) axis","Renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"The HPA axis is the primary stress response system. Chronic activation leads to elevated cortisol, which can cause hippocampal atrophy, immune suppression, and metabolic dysregulation. This is central to understanding stress-related disorders including PTSD, depression, and anxiety."},
        {domainId:1, q:"A patient presents with left-side neglect after a stroke. The lesion is most likely in the:", options:["Left frontal lobe","Left parietal lobe","Right parietal lobe","Right occipital lobe"], answer:2, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Hemispatial neglect typically results from right parietal lobe damage (particularly the right temporoparietal junction). The right hemisphere processes spatial attention for both visual fields, so damage produces left-side neglect. Left hemisphere damage rarely produces right neglect because the right hemisphere can compensate."},
        {domainId:1, q:"Which neurotransmitter is most directly implicated in Parkinson's disease?", options:["Serotonin","Acetylcholine","Dopamine","GABA"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Parkinson's disease results from degeneration of dopaminergic neurons in the substantia nigra, leading to dopamine depletion in the striatum. This produces the cardinal motor symptoms: resting tremor, bradykinesia, rigidity, and postural instability. Treatment with L-DOPA aims to restore dopamine levels."},
        {domainId:1, q:"Long-term potentiation (LTP) is considered a neural mechanism underlying:", options:["Sleep cycles","Learning and memory","Hunger regulation","Pain perception"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"LTP is a long-lasting increase in synaptic strength following high-frequency stimulation, first described in the hippocampus by Bliss and Lømo (1973). It involves NMDA receptor activation, calcium influx, and structural synaptic changes. LTP is the leading cellular model for how memories are encoded at the neural level."},
        {domainId:1, q:"The myelin sheath in the central nervous system is produced by:", options:["Schwann cells","Astrocytes","Oligodendrocytes","Microglia"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Oligodendrocytes produce myelin in the CNS, while Schwann cells myelinate peripheral nerves. Myelin acts as electrical insulation, enabling saltatory conduction and dramatically increasing neural transmission speed. Demyelination diseases like multiple sclerosis target oligodendrocytes, causing varied neurological symptoms."},

        // ===== Domain 2: Cognitive-Affective Bases of Behavior =====
        {domainId:2, q:"The availability heuristic leads people to:", options:["Evaluate probability based on how easily examples come to mind","Always overestimate rare events","Make decisions based on anchoring information","Ignore base rate information in all situations"], answer:0, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"The availability heuristic (Tversky & Kahneman, 1973) is a cognitive shortcut where people estimate probability based on how easily relevant examples come to mind. Events that are vivid, recent, or emotionally salient are overestimated (e.g., plane crashes vs. car accidents). This systematic bias affects clinical judgment and risk assessment."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Cognitive dissonance theory (Festinger, 1957) predicts that people will:", options:["Seek information that confirms existing beliefs","Experience discomfort when holding contradictory beliefs and be motivated to reduce it","Avoid making decisions whenever possible","Always change their behavior to match their attitudes"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Cognitive dissonance is the psychological discomfort from holding inconsistent cognitions (beliefs, attitudes, behaviors). People are motivated to reduce this dissonance through attitude change, behavior change, or rationalization. The theory has been extensively applied to understanding attitude change, decision-making, and persuasion."},
        {domainId:2, q:"The concept of 'emotional intelligence' (EQ), as popularized by Goleman, includes all EXCEPT:", options:["Self-awareness","Self-regulation","Abstract reasoning","Social skills"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Goleman's model of emotional intelligence includes five components: self-awareness, self-regulation, motivation, empathy, and social skills. Abstract reasoning is a component of cognitive intelligence (IQ), not emotional intelligence. The Mayer-Salovey model similarly focuses on perceiving, using, understanding, and managing emotions."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Working memory, as described by Baddeley's model, includes which components?", options:["Phonological loop, visuospatial sketchpad, and central executive","Short-term store and long-term store","Encoding, storage, and retrieval","Semantic memory and episodic memory"], answer:0, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Baddeley's (1986, 2000) working memory model includes: the phonological loop (verbal/acoustic information), visuospatial sketchpad (visual/spatial information), central executive (attention control and coordination), and the episodic buffer (added in 2000, integrates information across subsystems and links to long-term memory)."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Albert Ellis's Rational Emotive Behavior Therapy (REBT) identified which core irrational beliefs?", options:["All-or-nothing thinking, catastrophizing, and personalization","Demandingness, awfulizing, and low frustration tolerance","Learned helplessness and external locus of control","Negative automatic thoughts and cognitive schemas"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Ellis identified three core irrational beliefs: demandingness (rigid 'musts' and 'shoulds'), awfulizing (catastrophizing the consequences of unmet demands), and low frustration tolerance ('I can't stand it'). These beliefs are challenged through the ABCDE model: Activating event, Beliefs, Consequences, Disputing, and new Effective philosophy."},

        // ===== Domain 3: Social & Cultural Bases of Behavior =====
        {domainId:3, q:"According to the contact hypothesis (Allport, 1954), prejudice between groups can be reduced when:", options:["Groups are kept separate to avoid conflict","Contact occurs under conditions of equal status, common goals, intergroup cooperation, and institutional support","One group is clearly dominant over the other","Contact is brief and superficial"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Allport's contact hypothesis specifies four conditions for effective prejudice reduction: equal status between groups, common goals, intergroup cooperation (rather than competition), and support from authorities or institutions. Merely increasing contact without these conditions can actually increase prejudice. Meta-analyses confirm these conditions significantly moderate contact effects."},
        {domainId:3, q:"The Stanford Prison Experiment (Zimbardo, 1971) primarily demonstrated:", options:["The effectiveness of cognitive-behavioral interventions","The power of situational forces on behavior","The reliability of personality assessments","The importance of informed consent in research"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Zimbardo's experiment demonstrated how quickly normal individuals adopted abusive behaviors when placed in positions of power (guards) or became passive and submissive (prisoners). It highlighted the power of situational factors and social roles over individual dispositions. The study has been criticized for ethical violations and demand characteristics."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Microaggressions are defined as:", options:["Overt acts of discrimination","Brief, everyday exchanges that communicate hostile or derogatory messages to marginalized groups","Minor interpersonal conflicts between coworkers","Deliberate acts of racism"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Sue et al. (2007) defined microaggressions as brief, commonplace exchanges that convey denigrating messages to members of marginalized groups. They can be microassaults (deliberate), microinsults (insensitive), or microinvalidations (dismissing experiences). Their cumulative impact on mental health and well-being is well-documented in the literature."},
        {domainId:3, q:"According to Cross's model of Black racial identity development, the 'Encounter' stage is characterized by:", options:["Idealization of the dominant culture","A personal experience that challenges existing racial attitudes","Immersion in one's own racial/cultural identity","Internalization of a positive racial identity"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Cross's Nigrescence model (1971, 1995) includes: Pre-encounter (absorption of dominant culture values), Encounter (a significant experience that forces reexamination of racial attitudes), Immersion-Emersion (deep exploration of Black identity), and Internalization (secure, positive racial identity with capacity for multicultural relationships)."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Groupthink (Janis, 1972) is most likely to occur when:", options:["Group members have diverse backgrounds and opinions","The group is highly cohesive, isolated, and has a directive leader","Groups use systematic decision-making processes","Group members engage in critical evaluation"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Groupthink occurs in highly cohesive groups that are isolated from outside opinions, have a directive leader, and lack established procedures for critical evaluation. Symptoms include illusion of invulnerability, collective rationalization, and self-censorship. Janis used historical case studies (Bay of Pigs) to illustrate how groupthink leads to poor decisions."},

        // ===== Domain 4: Growth & Lifespan Development =====
        {domainId:4, q:"A child in Piaget's sensorimotor stage (0-2 years) is primarily characterized by:", options:["Symbolic thinking and pretend play","Understanding of conservation and classification","Knowledge gained through sensory experiences and motor actions","Abstract logical reasoning"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"The sensorimotor stage involves learning through direct sensory and motor interactions with the environment. Key achievements include object permanence (understanding objects exist when not visible, ~8 months), deferred imitation, and the beginning of representational thought. Language and symbolic play emerge at the end of this stage."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Harlow's research with rhesus monkeys primarily demonstrated:", options:["The importance of food in attachment formation","The primacy of contact comfort over food in attachment","The role of imprinting in social development","The effects of classical conditioning on infant behavior"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Harlow's (1958) studies showed that infant monkeys preferred the cloth 'mother' providing contact comfort over the wire 'mother' providing food. This challenged the behaviorist view that attachment is based on feeding and supported Bowlby's theory that attachment serves a protective, emotional function independent of nourishment."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Bronfenbrenner's ecological systems theory includes all of the following EXCEPT:", options:["Microsystem","Mesosystem","Psychosexual system","Macrosystem"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Bronfenbrenner's model includes five nested systems: microsystem (immediate settings), mesosystem (interactions between microsystems), exosystem (indirect influences), macrosystem (cultural values and laws), and chronosystem (changes over time). The psychosexual system belongs to Freud's developmental theory, not Bronfenbrenner's ecological model."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Selective optimization with compensation (SOC) is a developmental strategy primarily associated with:", options:["Childhood cognitive development","Adolescent identity formation","Successful aging","Prenatal development"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Baltes and Baltes (1990) proposed SOC as a framework for successful aging: Selection (narrowing goals to match capacities), Optimization (investing resources in chosen areas), and Compensation (using alternative means when abilities decline). The classic example is pianist Rubinstein reducing his repertoire (selection), practicing more (optimization), and slowing tempo before fast passages (compensation)."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Temperament, as described by Thomas and Chess (1977), includes which classification?", options:["Easy, difficult, and slow-to-warm-up","Secure, avoidant, and disorganized","Oral, anal, and phallic","Trust, autonomy, and initiative"], answer:0, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Thomas and Chess identified three temperament categories from the New York Longitudinal Study: easy (40% — regular rhythms, positive mood, adaptable), difficult (10% — irregular, intense, slow to adapt), and slow-to-warm-up (15% — initially withdrawn but gradually warming). About 35% of children didn't fit neatly into any category."},

        // ===== Domain 5: Assessment & Diagnosis =====
        {domainId:5, q:"The Rorschach Inkblot Test, when scored using the Exner Comprehensive System, provides information about:", options:["Only the patient's unconscious conflicts","Personality structure, emotion management, and cognitive processing","Intelligence quotient","Specific psychiatric diagnoses"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"The Exner Comprehensive System (1974, 2003) transformed the Rorschach from a subjective projective tool into a more standardized assessment. It provides information about personality structure, emotion management, cognitive processing style, interpersonal functioning, and self-perception. While controversial, meta-analyses show adequate validity for some indices."},
        {domainId:5, q:"In DSM-5, the Global Assessment of Functioning (GAF) scale was:", options:["Retained as a required axis","Replaced by the WHODAS 2.0 as the recommended disability measure","Made the primary diagnostic criterion","Combined with the personality disorders section"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"DSM-5 eliminated the multiaxial system including the GAF scale (Axis V). The World Health Organization Disability Assessment Schedule 2.0 (WHODAS 2.0) was recommended as an alternative measure of disability. The WHODAS 2.0 assesses six domains: cognition, mobility, self-care, getting along, life activities, and participation."},
        {domainId:5, q:"A test with a sensitivity of 95% means that:", options:["The test correctly identifies 95% of people who actually have the condition","The test correctly identifies 95% of people who do NOT have the condition","95% of all test results are accurate","The test has a 95% reliability coefficient"], answer:0, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Sensitivity (true positive rate) is the probability that a test correctly identifies individuals who have the condition. Specificity (true negative rate) is the probability of correctly identifying those without the condition. High sensitivity is important for screening tests (to avoid missing cases), while high specificity is important for confirmatory tests (to avoid false positives)."},
        {domainId:5, q:"Incremental validity refers to:", options:["The increase in test scores over time","The extent to which a test adds predictive value beyond existing information","The reliability of a test across multiple administrations","The construct validity of a new test measure"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Incremental validity assesses whether adding a new test or predictor significantly improves prediction beyond what is already available. For example, does adding a personality measure to an IQ test significantly improve prediction of job performance? This concept is crucial for justifying the cost and time of additional assessment measures."},
        {domainId:5, q:"The Beck Depression Inventory-II (BDI-II) is classified as:", options:["A projective personality test","A self-report symptom measure","A performance-based cognitive test","A structured diagnostic interview"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"The BDI-II is a 21-item self-report measure assessing depression severity over the past two weeks. Each item is rated 0-3, with total scores of 0-13 (minimal), 14-19 (mild), 20-28 (moderate), and 29-63 (severe). It is one of the most widely used and well-validated depression screening instruments in clinical practice and research."},

        // ===== Domain 6: Treatment/Intervention =====
        {domainId:6, q:"The transtheoretical model (Stages of Change) includes which stages?", options:["Denial, anger, bargaining, depression, acceptance","Precontemplation, contemplation, preparation, action, maintenance","Assessment, diagnosis, treatment, termination","Forming, storming, norming, performing"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Prochaska and DiClemente's (1983) transtheoretical model identifies five stages: Precontemplation (unaware of problem), Contemplation (considering change), Preparation (planning change), Action (implementing change), and Maintenance (sustaining change). The model emphasizes matching interventions to stage and recognizes that relapse is a normal part of the change process."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Which therapeutic approach emphasizes 'unconditional positive regard' as a core condition?", options:["Psychoanalytic therapy","Person-centered therapy","Cognitive-behavioral therapy","Strategic family therapy"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Carl Rogers' person-centered therapy identifies three core conditions: unconditional positive regard (non-judgmental acceptance), empathy (understanding the client's experience), and congruence/genuineness (therapist authenticity). Rogers believed these conditions are both necessary and sufficient for therapeutic change, regardless of specific techniques used."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Systematic desensitization, developed by Wolpe, combines:", options:["Free association and dream analysis","Relaxation training and graduated exposure","Cognitive restructuring and behavioral activation","Medication and psychotherapy"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Wolpe (1958) developed systematic desensitization based on the principle of reciprocal inhibition — anxiety cannot coexist with relaxation. The procedure involves: (1) learning progressive muscle relaxation, (2) constructing a fear hierarchy, and (3) pairing relaxation with progressively more anxiety-provoking stimuli (real or imagined). It is highly effective for specific phobias."},
        {domainId:6, q:"In structural family therapy (Minuchin), the concept of 'enmeshment' refers to:", options:["Healthy emotional connections between family members","Overly rigid boundaries between family subsystems","Excessive closeness and blurred boundaries between family members","Complete emotional detachment between family members"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Minuchin's structural family therapy distinguishes healthy boundaries from enmeshment (overly permeable boundaries, excessive emotional involvement, lack of individual autonomy) and disengagement (overly rigid boundaries, emotional distance). The therapist uses techniques like joining, restructuring, and enactment to modify dysfunctional family structures."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Eye Movement Desensitization and Reprocessing (EMDR) was originally developed to treat:", options:["Major depressive disorder","Post-traumatic stress disorder","Obsessive-compulsive disorder","Generalized anxiety disorder"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Francine Shapiro developed EMDR (1987) specifically for trauma processing. The eight-phase protocol involves bilateral stimulation (eye movements, tapping, or auditory tones) while processing traumatic memories. EMDR is now recognized by APA, WHO, and VA as an evidence-based treatment for PTSD, with efficacy comparable to trauma-focused CBT."},

        // ===== Domain 7: Research Methods =====
        {domainId:7, q:"A meta-analysis differs from a narrative literature review in that it:", options:["Is based on qualitative data only","Uses statistical methods to combine results across studies","Includes only randomized controlled trials","Does not require a systematic search strategy"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Meta-analysis uses quantitative statistical techniques (typically computing weighted effect sizes) to systematically combine results across multiple studies. This approach provides greater statistical power, more precise effect estimates, and can identify moderating variables. Unlike narrative reviews, meta-analyses follow explicit protocols for study selection, data extraction, and analysis."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Ecological validity refers to:", options:["The extent to which research findings generalize to real-world settings","The internal consistency of research measures","The statistical power of a research design","The degree to which participants are randomly assigned"], answer:0, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Ecological validity is a component of external validity that addresses whether findings from controlled research settings (e.g., laboratories) generalize to natural, real-world contexts. Laboratory experiments often sacrifice ecological validity for internal validity (control of confounds). This trade-off is a fundamental consideration in research design."},
        {domainId:7, q:"In a 2×3 factorial design, how many conditions are there in total?", options:["5","6","8","23"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"A factorial design with two factors (2 levels × 3 levels) produces 2 × 3 = 6 experimental conditions. Factorial designs allow researchers to examine main effects of each factor and their interaction effect. The interaction effect reveals whether the effect of one factor depends on the level of the other factor."},
        {domainId:7, q:"The Bonferroni correction is used to:", options:["Increase statistical power","Control for Type I error when making multiple comparisons","Improve effect size estimation","Adjust for non-normal distributions"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"When performing multiple statistical tests, the probability of at least one Type I error (false positive) increases. The Bonferroni correction divides the desired alpha level by the number of comparisons (e.g., α = .05/10 = .005). While effective at controlling Type I error, it is conservative and can increase Type II error (reducing power)."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Qualitative research methods are most appropriate when:", options:["The goal is to test specific hypotheses about causal relationships","The researcher wants to understand lived experiences and meaning-making","Large sample sizes are available","The phenomenon is well-understood and easily quantified"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Qualitative methods (phenomenology, grounded theory, ethnography, narrative analysis) are best suited for exploring complex phenomena, understanding lived experiences, generating theory, and studying processes that are difficult to quantify. They emphasize depth over breadth and use purposive rather than random sampling."},

        // ===== Domain 8: Professional Ethics =====
        {domainId:8, q:"When a psychologist receives a subpoena for client records, the psychologist should:", options:["Immediately release all records to the court","Destroy sensitive records before complying","Consult with an attorney and attempt to assert privilege on behalf of the client","Refuse to comply under all circumstances"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"A subpoena is not the same as a court order. The psychologist should: (1) notify the client, (2) consult with an attorney, (3) attempt to assert privilege or quash the subpoena if appropriate, (4) limit disclosure to what is legally required, and (5) only release records if compelled by a court order. Releasing all records without these steps violates confidentiality obligations."},
        {domainId:8, q:"The 'duty to warn' has been extended or modified in many states since Tarasoff. Which statement is MOST accurate?", options:["All states have identical duty-to-warn laws","Some states require only a duty to protect, not specifically to warn","The duty to warn has been eliminated in all states","The duty only applies to psychologists, not other mental health professionals"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"States vary significantly in their implementation of Tarasoff principles. Some require specific warnings to identifiable victims, others require protective actions (hospitalization, notifying police), and some have no statutory duty at all. Psychologists must know their specific state laws. The distinction between 'duty to warn' (telling the victim) and 'duty to protect' (taking any reasonable protective action) is clinically and legally important."},
        {domainId:8, q:"Multiple relationships (formerly 'dual relationships') are:", options:["Always unethical under APA guidelines","Unethical only when they impair objectivity, competence, or exploit the client","Acceptable as long as the client consents","Only problematic in rural or small-community settings"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"APA Standard 3.05 states that psychologists must avoid multiple relationships that could reasonably be expected to impair objectivity, competence, or effectiveness, or risk exploitation or harm. Not all multiple relationships are unethical — in rural or military settings, some overlap may be unavoidable. The key factors are potential for harm and impaired professional judgment."},
        {domainId:8, q:"Regarding child abuse reporting, psychologists:", options:["May use clinical judgment to decide whether to report","Are mandated reporters in all 50 states and must report suspected abuse","Only need to report confirmed abuse","Can maintain confidentiality if the child asks them not to report"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"All 50 states designate psychologists as mandated reporters of suspected child abuse and neglect. 'Suspected' is the threshold — proof or confirmation is not required. Failure to report can result in criminal charges and license revocation. Confidentiality does not override mandatory reporting obligations, and clinicians should inform clients of this limit at the outset of treatment."},
        {domainId:8, q:"The concept of 'informed consent' in psychology requires:", options:["Only a signed form","Providing information about procedures, risks, benefits, alternatives, and the right to withdraw","Consent from a legal guardian regardless of client age","Written consent in all circumstances"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"APA Standard 3.10 requires that informed consent include: the nature and purpose of the service, expected duration, fees, limits of confidentiality, risks and benefits, alternatives, and the right to withdraw at any time. Consent is an ongoing process, not just a form. Special considerations apply for minors, individuals with diminished capacity, and mandated clients."}
    ];

    batch3.forEach(q => {
        const domain = EPPPData.domains.find(d => d.id === q.domainId);
        if (domain) {
            domain.questions.push({
                q: q.q, options: q.options, answer: q.answer,
                difficulty: q.difficulty, rationale: q.rationale,
                domainId: q.domainId, domainName: domain.name
            });
        }
    });

    console.log(`PasstheEPPP: Loaded ${batch3.length} additional questions (batch 3).`);
})();


