/* PasstheEPPP — Expanded Question Bank Batch 4 */
(function(){
    if (typeof EPPPData === 'undefined') return;

    const batch4 = [
        // ===== Domain 1: Biological Bases of Behavior =====
        {domainId:1, q:"Damage to the hippocampus would most likely result in:", options:["Inability to form new explicit memories","Loss of all previously stored memories","Impaired motor coordination","Changes in personality and emotional regulation"], answer:0, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"The hippocampus is critical for consolidating new explicit (declarative) memories from short-term to long-term storage. Bilateral hippocampal damage, as in patient H.M. (Henry Molaison), produces severe anterograde amnesia while leaving procedural memory and most retrograde memories relatively intact."},
        {domainId:1, q:"The corpus callosum's primary function is to:", options:["Regulate emotional responses","Connect the two cerebral hemispheres allowing interhemispheric communication","Control voluntary movement","Process auditory information"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"The corpus callosum is the largest white matter tract in the brain, containing approximately 200 million axons that connect the left and right hemispheres. Split-brain studies by Sperry and Gazzaniga demonstrated that severing the corpus callosum disrupts interhemispheric transfer of information, revealing hemispheric specialization."},
        {domainId:1, q:"Which structure is part of the limbic system and plays a key role in emotion, motivation, and memory?", options:["Cerebellum","Medulla oblongata","Amygdala","Pons"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"The amygdala is a key limbic structure involved in emotional processing, particularly fear and threat detection. It modulates memory consolidation by enhancing storage of emotionally arousing events. The limbic system also includes the hippocampus, hypothalamus, cingulate cortex, and related structures."},
        {domainId:1, q:"Phenylketonuria (PKU) demonstrates which concept in behavioral genetics?", options:["Gene-environment interaction","Polygenic inheritance","Epigenetic modification","Genomic imprinting"], answer:0, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"PKU is a classic example of gene-environment interaction. The genetic mutation affects phenylalanine metabolism, but intellectual disability only occurs if the individual is exposed to dietary phenylalanine. Restrictive diet (environmental modification) prevents the negative outcome despite the genetic predisposition, illustrating that genes set a range of possible outcomes but environment determines the specific outcome."},
        {domainId:1, q:"The reticular activating system (RAS) is primarily responsible for:", options:["Visual processing","Regulating arousal, wakefulness, and attention","Language production","Motor planning"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"The reticular activating system is a network of neurons in the brainstem that regulates arousal, wakefulness, and alertness. Damage to the RAS can result in coma or persistent vegetative state. It acts as a gatekeeper for sensory information reaching the cortex and plays a role in the sleep-wake cycle."},

        // ===== Domain 2: Cognitive-Affective Bases of Behavior =====
        {domainId:2, q:"The 'weapon focus effect' in eyewitness testimony demonstrates:", options:["Enhanced memory for all details during threatening events","Attentional narrowing that impairs memory for peripheral details","Superior recall by police officers","The impact of post-event information on memory"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"The weapon focus effect occurs when the presence of a weapon captures the witness's attention, drawing focus away from other details such as the perpetrator's face. This attentional narrowing results in better memory for the weapon but poorer memory for other aspects of the event, reducing the accuracy of eyewitness identification."},
        {domainId:2, q:"According to Sternberg's triarchic theory of intelligence, practical intelligence involves:", options:["The ability to analyze and evaluate ideas","The ability to generate novel and creative solutions","The ability to adapt to, shape, and select environments","The speed of information processing"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Sternberg's triarchic theory includes: analytical intelligence (evaluating, comparing, contrasting), creative intelligence (inventing, discovering, imagining), and practical intelligence ('street smarts' — adapting to, shaping, and selecting real-world environments). Practical intelligence is often measured through tacit knowledge rather than traditional IQ tests."},
        {domainId:2, q:"The phi phenomenon, demonstrated by Wertheimer, is an example of:", options:["Classical conditioning","Operant conditioning","Gestalt perception","Cognitive dissonance"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"The phi phenomenon (apparent motion from sequential flashing lights) was demonstrated by Wertheimer (1912) and is foundational to Gestalt psychology. It illustrates that perception is not simply the sum of sensory inputs but involves the brain organizing stimuli into meaningful wholes — 'the whole is different from the sum of its parts.'"},
        {domainId:2, q:"In Gardner's theory of multiple intelligences, which type involves sensitivity to the feelings and moods of others?", options:["Intrapersonal intelligence","Interpersonal intelligence","Linguistic intelligence","Existential intelligence"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Gardner's multiple intelligences include: linguistic, logical-mathematical, spatial, bodily-kinesthetic, musical, interpersonal (understanding others), intrapersonal (understanding self), and naturalistic. Interpersonal intelligence involves sensitivity to others' feelings, moods, and motivations — critical for therapists, teachers, and leaders."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Transfer-appropriate processing theory suggests that memory is best when:", options:["Information is deeply processed","Encoding and retrieval conditions match","Material is rehearsed repeatedly","Information is organized hierarchically"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Transfer-appropriate processing (Morris et al., 1977) proposes that memory performance depends on the match between encoding processes and retrieval demands. For example, if you study material by focusing on how words sound (phonological processing), you'll perform better on a rhyme recognition test than a semantic test, even though semantic processing is 'deeper.'"},

        // ===== Domain 3: Social & Cultural Bases =====
        {domainId:3, q:"The fundamental attribution error refers to the tendency to:", options:["Attribute one's own failures to external factors","Overestimate dispositional factors and underestimate situational factors when explaining others' behavior","Assume others share our beliefs and attitudes","Make more favorable attributions for in-group members"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"The fundamental attribution error (FAE), also called correspondence bias, is the tendency to explain others' behavior in terms of their personality or disposition while underestimating situational influences. When someone cuts us off in traffic, we think 'bad driver' (dispositional) rather than 'having an emergency' (situational). This bias is more prominent in individualistic cultures."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Social facilitation theory predicts that the presence of others will:", options:["Always improve performance","Always impair performance","Improve performance on well-learned tasks and impair performance on novel tasks","Have no significant effect on performance"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Zajonc's (1965) social facilitation theory proposes that the mere presence of others increases arousal, which enhances the dominant response. For well-practiced tasks, the dominant response is correct (improved performance). For complex or novel tasks, the dominant response may be incorrect (impaired performance). This explains why expert performers thrive with audiences while novices often 'choke.'"},
        {domainId:3, q:"According to Tajfel's social identity theory, in-group favoritism:", options:["Only occurs in the presence of realistic competition for resources","Can occur based on minimal and arbitrary group distinctions","Is limited to ethnic and racial groups","Requires a history of intergroup conflict"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Tajfel's minimal group paradigm demonstrated that merely categorizing people into groups — even on trivial criteria like preference for a painting — was sufficient to produce in-group favoritism and out-group discrimination. This suggests that the cognitive act of categorization itself, independent of competition or conflict, can generate intergroup bias."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Stereotype threat is MOST likely to impair performance when:", options:["The individual is unaware of the stereotype","The task is perceived as irrelevant to the stereotyped ability","The individual strongly identifies with the stereotyped domain","The testing environment is anonymous and low-stakes"], answer:2, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Stereotype threat is strongest when individuals strongly identify with the domain being tested (e.g., women who value math performance on a math test). Domain identification increases the threat's relevance and the pressure to disprove the stereotype. Additionally, high-stakes testing situations and environments that make the stereotype salient (e.g., being the only minority) amplify the effect."},

        // ===== Domain 4: Growth & Lifespan Development =====
        {domainId:4, q:"According to Piaget, the ability to think about thinking (metacognition) first emerges during which stage?", options:["Sensorimotor","Preoperational","Concrete operational","Formal operational"], answer:3, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Metacognition — the ability to think about one's own thinking processes — is a hallmark of Piaget's formal operational stage (age 11+). This stage also introduces hypothetico-deductive reasoning, abstract thought, and systematic problem-solving. Not all individuals reach this stage, and some may only use formal operations in areas of expertise."},
        {domainId:4, q:"In Marcia's identity status model, 'moratorium' is characterized by:", options:["High commitment, low exploration","Low commitment, low exploration","High exploration, low commitment","High commitment, high exploration"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Marcia expanded Erikson's identity vs. role confusion stage into four identity statuses based on exploration and commitment: Identity Achievement (explored + committed), Moratorium (actively exploring, not yet committed), Foreclosure (committed without exploration), and Identity Diffusion (no exploration or commitment). Moratorium represents an active search for identity."},
        {domainId:4, q:"The concept of 'scaffolding' in education was introduced by:", options:["Piaget","Vygotsky","Bruner","Montessori"], answer:2, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"While scaffolding is closely associated with Vygotsky's ZPD concept, the term 'scaffolding' was actually coined by Jerome Bruner, David Wood, and Gail Ross (1976). They described how tutors adjusted their support based on the learner's current performance, gradually removing support as competence increased — like construction scaffolding removed as a building takes shape."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Gilligan's theory of moral development differs from Kohlberg's primarily by emphasizing:", options:["Universal moral principles","An ethic of care and responsibility in relationships","Reward and punishment in moral reasoning","Cultural relativism in moral judgments"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Carol Gilligan (1982) criticized Kohlberg's model as biased toward a male justice/rights orientation. She proposed that women's moral reasoning emphasizes an ethic of care — focusing on relationships, responsibility, and avoiding harm. Her three levels progress from self-interest to self-sacrifice to balancing care for self and others. However, research has not consistently supported gender differences in moral reasoning."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Stranger anxiety typically first appears at approximately:", options:["2-3 months","6-8 months","12-15 months","18-24 months"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Stranger anxiety typically emerges around 6-8 months, coinciding with the development of object permanence and the ability to discriminate familiar from unfamiliar faces. It peaks around 12-15 months and usually diminishes by age 2. Separation anxiety follows a similar timeline. Both are considered normal developmental milestones reflecting healthy attachment."},

        // ===== Domain 5: Assessment & Diagnosis =====
        {domainId:5, q:"A psychological test has high face validity when:", options:["It accurately predicts future behavior","It appears to measure what it is supposed to measure","It correlates highly with other tests of the same construct","It produces consistent results over time"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Face validity is the extent to which a test appears, on the surface, to measure what it claims to. Unlike content or criterion validity, face validity is not a technical measure of validity but rather subjective assessment of test-taker perception. While important for test acceptance and motivation, a test can have high face validity but poor actual validity, and vice versa."},
        {domainId:5, q:"The WISC-V is most appropriately used for:", options:["Adults ages 18-90","Children ages 6-16","Infants ages 0-3","Elderly adults ages 65+"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"The Wechsler Intelligence Scale for Children, Fifth Edition (WISC-V) is designed for children ages 6:0 to 16:11. The Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale (WAIS-IV/V) covers ages 16-90+, and the Wechsler Preschool and Primary Scale of Intelligence (WPPSI-IV) covers ages 2:6 to 7:7. This family of tests is the most widely used for intellectual assessment."},
        {domainId:5, q:"In a positively skewed distribution, the mean is:", options:["Equal to the median","Less than the median","Greater than the median","Equal to the mode"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"In a positively skewed distribution (tail extends to the right), the mean is pulled toward the tail and is greater than the median, which is greater than the mode: Mode < Median < Mean. In a negatively skewed distribution, this order reverses. This is important for understanding which measure of central tendency best represents the data."},
        {domainId:5, q:"The difference between the DSM-5 and the ICD-11 is that:", options:["The DSM-5 is used worldwide while the ICD-11 is only used in the U.S.","The ICD-11 is produced by the WHO and is used internationally, while the DSM-5 is published by the APA and primarily used in the U.S.","The ICD-11 only covers mental disorders","The DSM-5 includes all medical conditions"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"The ICD (International Classification of Diseases) is published by the World Health Organization and is the global standard for health statistics and clinical coding, covering all diseases. The DSM (Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders) is published by the American Psychiatric Association and focuses specifically on mental disorders. Both systems have been harmonized in many areas but differ in some diagnostic criteria."},

        // ===== Domain 6: Treatment/Intervention =====
        {domainId:6, q:"Paradoxical intention, a logotherapy technique, involves:", options:["Prescribing the symptom or encouraging the feared behavior","Gradually exposing the client to feared stimuli","Interpreting unconscious motivations","Challenging irrational beliefs directly"], answer:0, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Viktor Frankl's paradoxical intention involves prescribing the symptom — asking the client to intentionally do or wish for the very thing they fear. For example, a client with insomnia is told to try to stay awake, or a client who fears sweating is told to try to sweat as much as possible. This removes the anticipatory anxiety that perpetuates the symptom. It is related to but distinct from strategic therapy's paradoxical interventions."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Solution-focused brief therapy (SFBT) is characterized by:", options:["Extensive exploration of past traumas","Focus on exceptions to the problem and building on existing strengths","Long-term treatment over many years","Interpretation of transference and countertransference"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"SFBT (de Shazer & Berg) focuses on solutions rather than problems. Key techniques include: the miracle question ('If a miracle happened overnight and your problem was solved, how would you know?'), exception questions (times when the problem didn't occur), scaling questions (1-10 ratings), and compliments. Treatment is typically brief (3-5 sessions)."},
        {domainId:6, q:"In psychoanalytic therapy, countertransference refers to:", options:["The client's unconscious feelings toward the therapist","The therapist's unconscious emotional reactions to the client","The therapist's use of interpretation","The client's resistance to treatment"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Countertransference involves the therapist's unconscious emotional reactions to the client, often triggered by the client's transference. Modern psychodynamic theory views countertransference as both a potential hindrance and a valuable source of clinical information about the client's relational patterns. Managing countertransference through self-awareness, supervision, and personal therapy is considered essential."},
        {domainId:6, q:"The concept of 'therapeutic window of tolerance' (Siegel) refers to:", options:["The optimal time frame for scheduling therapy sessions","The zone of arousal in which a person can effectively process information and emotions","The length of time a client should be in therapy","The range of therapeutic techniques a therapist should use"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Dan Siegel's window of tolerance describes the optimal zone of arousal where a person can effectively process emotions, think clearly, and function well. Above the window, individuals experience hyperarousal (anxiety, rage, hypervigilance). Below it, hypoarousal (numbness, dissociation, collapse). Trauma treatment aims to help clients widen their window and develop skills to return to it."},

        // ===== Domain 7: Research Methods =====
        {domainId:7, q:"The primary advantage of a within-subjects design over a between-subjects design is:", options:["Elimination of order effects","Reduced demand characteristics","Increased statistical power by controlling for individual differences","Greater external validity"], answer:2, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Within-subjects (repeated measures) designs use the same participants in all conditions, eliminating individual differences as a source of error variance. This increases statistical power, requiring fewer participants to detect effects. However, order effects (practice, fatigue, carryover) are a concern and must be controlled through counterbalancing."},
        {domainId:7, q:"When a researcher measures aggression by counting the number of times a child hits a doll, this is an example of:", options:["A self-report measure","An operational definition","A theoretical construct","A mediating variable"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"An operational definition specifies the exact procedures used to measure or manipulate a variable. 'Aggression' is an abstract construct; 'number of hits on a Bobo doll in 10 minutes' is its operational definition. Good operational definitions are specific, measurable, and replicable. The validity of research depends on how well operational definitions represent the intended constructs."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Selection bias in research occurs when:", options:["The measuring instrument is unreliable","Participants are not randomly assigned or selected, leading to non-equivalent groups","The researcher knows which group each participant is in","The dependent variable is poorly operationalized"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Selection bias threatens internal validity when participants are not randomly assigned to conditions, potentially creating pre-existing differences between groups. For example, if volunteers choose to be in the treatment group, they may be more motivated than control participants, confounding the results. Random assignment is the primary defense against selection bias."},
        {domainId:7, q:"A negative correlation between hours of sleep and anxiety levels means:", options:["More sleep causes less anxiety","As sleep hours increase, anxiety levels tend to decrease","There is no relationship between sleep and anxiety","Sleep and anxiety are causally related"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"A negative correlation indicates an inverse relationship — as one variable increases, the other tends to decrease. However, correlation does not imply causation. A third variable (e.g., physical health, stress) could explain both poor sleep and high anxiety. Only experimental manipulation with random assignment can establish causal relationships."},

        // ===== Domain 8: Professional Ethics =====
        {domainId:8, q:"When providing services to an organization, the psychologist's primary ethical obligation regarding confidentiality extends to:", options:["Only the organization that hired them","The individuals being assessed, who should be informed about the nature and purpose of the assessment","The referral source exclusively","No one, as organizational work is exempt from confidentiality requirements"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"APA Standard 3.11 requires that psychologists providing services to organizations inform individuals about the nature and purpose of activities, who will receive the information, and limits of confidentiality. Even in organizational settings, individual rights must be respected. The psychologist must balance obligations to both the organization and the individuals being assessed."},
        {domainId:8, q:"A psychologist moving to a new state must:", options:["Automatically practice under their previous state's license","Obtain licensure in the new state before practicing","Only notify the APA of the move","Practice under supervision indefinitely"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Psychology licensure is state-specific; a license in one state does not authorize practice in another. The psychologist must meet the new state's requirements, which may include additional examinations, supervised practice hours, or documentation. The ASPPB's PSYPACT (Psychology Interjurisdictional Compact) allows telepsychology across participating states but full interstate mobility still requires new licensure."},
        {domainId:8, q:"In research ethics, the concept of 'equipoise' refers to:", options:["Equal distribution of resources across research groups","Genuine uncertainty about whether one treatment is superior to another","The balance between risks and benefits of participating","Equal representation of demographic groups in samples"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Clinical equipoise exists when there is genuine uncertainty within the expert medical/psychological community about which treatment is superior. This concept justifies randomized controlled trials — if we already knew which treatment was better, it would be unethical to assign participants to the inferior condition. Equipoise is a core ethical requirement for clinical trial design."},
        {domainId:8, q:"Test security refers to a psychologist's obligation to:", options:["Keep therapy notes in a locked cabinet","Protect the integrity of test materials and prevent unauthorized access to test content","Ensure clients take tests in a secure setting","Report test fraud to the APA"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"APA Standard 9.11 requires psychologists to protect the integrity and security of tests. This includes not releasing test items, protocols, or scoring criteria to unauthorized persons. In the digital age, this extends to preventing test content from appearing online. Compromised test security undermines the validity and fairness of assessments for all examinees."}
    ];

    batch4.forEach(q => {
        const domain = EPPPData.domains.find(d => d.id === q.domainId);
        if (domain) {
            domain.questions.push({
                q: q.q, options: q.options, answer: q.answer,
                difficulty: q.difficulty, rationale: q.rationale,
                domainId: q.domainId, domainName: domain.name
            });
        }
    });

    console.log(`PasstheEPPP: Loaded ${batch4.length} additional questions (batch 4).`);
})();


